Add assertions to MarkCommand and DeleteCommand
commitResults.messageBody:
Add assertions to the execute() method in both MarkCommand and
DeleteCommand to verify that the taskList, ui, and storage parameters
are not null before use.

These assertions serve as precondition checks that document the
expected contract for the execute() method. Since these commands
depend on all three parameters being valid to function correctly,
the assertions help catch programming errors early during development
if null references are accidentally passed.

This follows the defensive programming practice of verifying
assumptions at method entry points, making bugs easier to detect
and diagnose during testing.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add assertions to Task constructors
commitResults.messageBody:
Add assertions to Task, Deadline, and Event constructors to validate
that required parameters are not null or empty before object creation.

In the Task base class, assertions verify that the description is not
null and not empty after trimming, and that the task type is not null.
In Deadline, assertions check that the deadline string is provided.
In Event, assertions verify both start and end time strings are valid.

These precondition checks document the contract that all tasks must
have meaningful descriptions and valid time information. The assertions
help catch cases where empty or null values might slip through input
validation, making it easier to identify the source of data issues
during development and testing.

By validating at construction time, we ensure that no task objects
can exist in an invalid state, maintaining data integrity throughout
the application lifecycle.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add assertions to Parser, Storage, and TaskList
commitResults.messageBody:
Add precondition assertions to key methods in Parser, Storage, and
TaskList classes to validate input parameters and document expected
conditions.

In Parser, assertions verify that the command string passed to parse()
is not null, and that the index string in parseTaskIndex() is not null.
An additional postcondition assertion confirms the parsed index is
non-negative after validation logic.

In Storage, assertions check that the file path constructor parameter
is not null or empty, and that the task list passed to save() is valid.

In TaskList, assertions verify that tasks added are not null and that
index parameters for getTask() and removeTask() are non-negative,
catching invalid indices before ArrayList operations.

These assertions document the contract expected by each method and
serve as early-warning guards against programming errors. They make
the codebase more maintainable by explicitly stating assumptions that
callers must satisfy, and help debug issues by failing fast when
preconditions are violated during development.

commitResults.messageTitle: Refactor add and delete commands
commitResults.messageBody:
Replace duplicated save logic in add and delete command classes
with the shared helper in Command. This removes repeated code and
keeps storage writes consistent across commands.

Simplify execute() methods by using the base class helper while
preserving existing behavior. This improves readability and makes
future changes easier to apply in one place.

commitResults.messageTitle: Refactor list and mark commands
commitResults.messageBody:
Update list, mark, and unmark commands to use the shared task list
formatter in the base Command class instead of duplicating string
building logic in each command.

This removes repeated code, keeps formatting consistent, and makes
the execute() methods shorter and easier to read without changing
their behavior.

Add tag and untag commands
commitResults.messageBody:
Introduce tag and untag commands to attach and remove tags on tasks
using the syntax `tag <index> #tag` and `untag <index> #tag`.

These commands validate index and tag format, then persist the
updates through the shared storage helper, giving users a simple
way to label tasks for organization.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add tagging support to task models
commitResults.messageBody:
Extend Task, Deadline, Event, and ToDo to support tags that are
stored and shown with tasks. The base Task class now manages tag
data and provides shared formatting helpers.

Deadline, Event, and ToDo append tag display output and include
tags when serializing for storage. This keeps tag handling
consistent across all task types while preserving existing behavior.
